english:
  title: Record of the Restoration of the Tower of Caring for the People
  author: Lee Woo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Along the slopes of the Taebaek Mountains lie towns whose beauty draws from mountain and water alike. Among them, Yeongcheon, positioned to the south, captures the finest vistas. When a tower was raised north of the guest lodge, it was set precisely at this supreme location—a place that should have been named for its scenery. Yet it was called the Tower of Caring for the People, forsaking mere beauty to enshrine something real.

    During the Xuande years, the magistrate Gwon Gong-sang of Yeonggye, within months of taking office, brought prosperity and plenty to the people. With surplus resources, he turned first to restore the building for visiting officials. Choosing an excellent northern site with fine earth and timber, the people competed to contribute and laborers worked with vigor. Within a year, the tower was complete. When Inspector Hong Yeo-bang made his rounds to the prefecture, he celebrated the tower's completion and praised Magistrate Gwon's governance. He hung the name plaque and composed a record to honor them both—proof that through fair judgment, official records capture truth rather than hollow praise.

    My friend Gwon Hyeop-ji, the magistrate's own grandson, resigned from his post as magistrate of the capital in spring of the year of Gapsu to attend his aging parents. When he arrived in Yeongcheon, the people rejoiced, dancing and beating drums in celebration: "Today we have gained the grandson of our great magistrate again!" Within years, the whole region flourished in renewed harmony.

    One day, Gwon ascended the tower and sighed: "When a public building deteriorates, officials must restore it—how much more so when it was built by my ancestors! The tower now stands nearly ninety years completed, fallen into disrepair for decades. Yet through many changes of officials, none renewed it. That it waited until today—is this not Heaven's will?" He called the people and told them: "This tower was built by our grandfathers working together. Now it has fallen to ruin. Is the duty of restoration not upon us both?" The people stirred themselves with resolve, and without needing agreement, they worked as one. The broken roof tiles, rotting beams and railings, and damaged walls—all were made new. The support beams, pillars, and foundations that could endure were left untouched. When the repairs were finished and the new lacquer and cinnabar gleamed, the labor expended was far less than before, yet the resulting splendor doubled.

    Though built by the people's strength, the people forgot their toil—it was merely restored, not rebuilt. Thus the mulberry tree of ancestral memory remains, carrying the gratitude of past generations.

    Alas! Magistrate Gwon first called forth his love for the people; his grandson answers with filial piety. Grandfather and grandson connected, linked through time—through the governance of one family flows the administration of an entire county. Can such transformation be measured? The ancients said: "Teaching through words breeds dispute; teaching through example brings compliance." Is this not teaching through example? This tower shall not merely store sensual pleasures or display the sun and moon. When one ascends its heights and sees fields of suffering, one recalls the hardship in each grain of rice. Beholding those who labor under burdens, one understands the weariness of toil. When wind comes, one discerns the difference between yin and yang; when summer rains fall, one contemplates the sorrows of common folk. This too becomes part of caring for the people.

    Moreover, Yeongcheon lies east of my home in Yean, and when my term ends and I return to the capital, I shall surely pass through on the way to visit my parents. Then, let us grasp wine cups atop this tower. Looking south to the ruins of the Tower of No-faith, feeling the chill of pines—as if touched by the righteous spirit of Jeong Seup-in warding off evil—and gazing west to Buseok Temple, where shadowed caves grow dark and the halls fall silent, as if glimpsing the confusion of Yi In-bo meeting spirits—when we behold the marketplace now fallen to desolation where imperial carriages once rested, when we question the miller and sigh at the hidden meaning in tales of dragon and fish—these are the beautiful vistas from this tower, resources for our future inquiry. Yet I ask nothing more of the tower's keeper. Having shared this with you, I retire to write this record.
  footnotes:
    - The Tower of Caring for the People (자민루) takes its name from the Confucian virtue of caring for the common people, emphasizing the magistrate's responsibility to their welfare rather than seeking beauty for its own sake.
    - The cyclical year of Gapsu (甲戌) refers to 1434 in the Gregorian calendar, during Korea's Joseon Dynasty under King Sejong.
    - The references to historical figures like Jeong Seup-in and Yi In-bo, along with the temples and ruins mentioned, ground the poem in specific local memories and legends of the Yeongcheon region.
    - The poem's concluding meditation—observing fields, laborers, and natural phenomena from the tower's height—reflects the Confucian ideal of the magistrate as one whose personal moral cultivation manifests in compassion for all people.
